    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-09-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-09-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="100"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d100">
                <head>100. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                        >Vance</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1"
                        >Carter</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d100fn1">Source: Carter Library, National
                        Security Affairs, Brzezinski Material, Subject File, Box 19, Evening Reports
                        (State), 9/77. Secret. <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName>
                        initialed the memorandum and wrote: “<persName corresp="#p_VCR_1"
                            >Cy</persName>.” All brackets are in the original except those
                        indicating text omitted by the editors or that remains classified.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-09-19">September 19, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1. <hi rend="italic">Intelligence Committee on Panama</hi>—Ambassadors <persName
                        corresp="#p_BE_1">Bunker</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_LSM_1"
                        >Linowitz</persName> testified along with <persName corresp="#p_TS_1"
                        >Stansfield Turner</persName> today before <persName corresp="#p_IDK_1"
                        >Inouye</persName>’s Intelligence Committee on the question of whether or
                    not intelligence leaks and/or threats of exposure by the Panamanians affected
                    the treaty negotiations. At the conclusion of the session, <persName
                        corresp="#p_IDK_1">Inouye</persName> read a statement to the press as
                    follows:</p>
                <quote>
                    <p>“The Committee has no evidence or reason to believe or conclude that <gloss
                            target="#t_US_2">U.S.</gloss> intelligence activities have in any way
                        affected the final results of the Panama Canal treaties negotiations.”</p>
                </quote>
                <p>While you can be expected to face a question at your next press conference as to
                    whether or not the United States conducted intelligence activities against
                    Panama, <persName corresp="#p_IDK_1">Inouye</persName>’s clean bill of health
                    for the treaties should protect them from further fallout,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d100fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJE_1">Carter</persName> wrote in the left margin:
                            “<hi rend="italic">good</hi>.”</note> [<hi rend="italic">1½ lines not
                        declassified</hi>] In view of last week’s leak from the Intelligence
                    Committee, <persName corresp="#p_IDK_1">Inouye</persName> is making every
                    conceivable effort to avoid further embarrassment.<note n="3" xml:id="d100fn3"
                        >Presumably a reference to the <gloss target="#t_CBS_1">CBS</gloss> News
                        report. See <ref target="#d97fn2">footnote 2, Document 97.</ref>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <p>[Omitted here is information unrelated to Panama.]</p>
            </div>
